title: Indonesia Earthquake Photos Show Wide Damage
description: The quake that toppled hundreds of building on the island of Java also blocked roads needed to get victims medical help.

title: In Women and Nonbinary People, Monkeypox Cases May Have Been Missed
description: Despite monkeypox fading from public attention, scientists are still learning how it spreads — including without sexual contact or any symptoms.

title: Bao Tong, 90, Dies; Top Chinese Official Imprisoned After Tiananmen
description: He helped design China’s political reforms in the 1980s and tried to avert the bloodshed that ended the democracy protests. After prison, he became a critic of the party.

title: Your Tuesday Briefing: Indonesia’s Deadly Earthquake
description: Plus Iranian players protest at the World Cup and “Neighbours” will start filming again.

title: The UN’s Nuclear Watchdog Calls for Protection of the Zaporizhzhia Plant
description: At the Zaporizhzhia power plant, the reactors have been shut down since September as a safety measure.

title: The Nature Conservancy Buys Insurance to Protect Hawaii’s Coral Reefs
description: If worsening coastal storms damage the reefs, the Nature Conservancy will get a payout and use the money to repair the coral — work that state officials can’t afford to do.

title: Iran Arrests 2 Actresses for Participating in Protests
description: Hengameh Ghaziani and Katayoun Riahi were detained after removing their head scarves and criticizing the government.

title: 1947: Rail Walkout in Marseilles Halts Traffic
description: The number of strikers in the French port city reached 100,000, with thousands of passengers stranded and communication disrupted.

title: Jacob Zuma’s Release Was Unlawful, South African Court Rules
description: The Supreme Court decision raises the possibility that former President Jacob Zuma, who was granted medical parole from a contempt-of-court sentence, may have to return to prison.

title: Netanyahu Awarded Damages After a Predecessor Called Him ‘Mentally Ill’
description: The Israeli prime minister-designate, Benjamin Netanyahu, and his family won a libel suit against a former prime minister, Ehud Olmert, but got far less compensation than they had demanded.

title: U.N. Nuclear Watchdog Urges Protective Area Around Power Plant
description: The head of the International Atomic Energy Agency says that Russian strikes on energy infrastructure threaten electricity lines that power cooling at several nuclear plants.

title: Powerful Earthquake Kills Dozens in Indonesia
description: The quake near the town of Cianjur destroyed hundreds of buildings, and officials expected the death toll of 61 to rise.

title: Gambling’s Spread
description: The popularity of sports betting has exploded in recent years in the U.S.

title: Somalia Braces for Famine, Trapped Between Al Shabab and Drought
description: The worst drought in 40 years is pushing Somalia to the brink. If it triggers a rare famine declaration, the militant group Al Shabab will also be to blame.

title: On the River at Night, Ambushing Russians
description: Ukrainian units plying the Dnipro River venture behind enemy lines under the cover of darkness, carrying out reconnaissance and sabotage.

title: Would You Pay $1,000 to See the World’s Biggest Lizards?
description: Indonesia wants to make it vastly more expensive to see the country’s famous Komodo dragons. The local tourism industry is up in arms.

title: Inside the Saudi Strategy to Keep the World Hooked on Oil
description: The kingdom is working to keep fossil fuels at the center of the world economy for decades to come by lobbying, funding research and using its diplomatic muscle to obstruct climate action.

title: Your Monday Briefing
description: A nightclub shooting in Colorado kills five.
